default8
default.
default              
defaultThe 
defaultWest Midlands
default notes that the 
defaultDfTs
default National Transport Model has identified that traffic on the strategic highway network is forecast to grow 
defaultby 46% for strategic road network and an average of 43% for all roads and 41% for all other roads
default in the central growth forecast
default,
default 
defaultunderpinned by population and economic growth along with technology 
defaultenhancements
default to motoring
default and propulsion
default. 
default&#xa0;
default1
default9
default.
default              
defaultWith the West Midlands alone predicted to see an increase of 10% approx in population by 2026, the 
defaultWest Midlands
default believes the fundamentals underpinning the need to travel are valid. Uncertainty therefore only focuses on the levels of economic growth and future technological transport changes
default which, if decoupled 
defaultfrom carbon fuel sources, could see the cost of motorin
defaultg decline
default.
default20
default.
default              
defaultThe 
defaultWest Midlands
default 
defaultbelieves
default even with the levels of uncertainty outlined by the 
defaultDfT
default, there should be Government 
defaultconcern of the consequences of these forecasts. 
defaultEven the lowest scenario of growth, traffic would increase by 23% by 2040
default with hig
defaulthest range seeing growth of 76% by 2040
default. 
default21.
default              
defaultThe Government should not look to repeat approach of the past and undertake a ‘predict and provide’ but rather ensure a robust ‘predict, manage and provide’ to ensure investment in alternative transport 
defaultinfrastructure to ensure future road traffic growth is minimised.
default Investment in rail, buses, walking and cycling will help minimise traffic growth whilst improving access to jobs, improving health, air quality and reduce carbon emissions.
default22
default.
default              
defaultT
defaulthe 
defaultWest Midl
defaultands
default would be extremely concerned at the consequence of 
defaulteven just a 23.6
default% increase in traffic on the M6 t
defaulthrough the metropolitan area. Such traffic growth would mean major impacts to 
defaultour economy, air quality and other pollution 
defaultand thus
default to our residents an
defaultd businesses. 
default23
default.
default              
defaultFinally, the 
defaultWest Midlands
default 
defaultbelieves
default 
defaultthat 
defaultthe 
defaultDfT
default should not just focus on the growth and implications of future road traffic growth predictions. The 
defaultDfT
default national transport model predicts between 21-54% 
