defaultQdefault5default. What mechanisms are there for Government tdefaulto increase investment in strategic roads and attract new investors? Are there good examples from other countries that could be applied in the UK?default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default33
default.
default              
defaultFrom the 
defaultWest Midlands
default experience, there appear to be two models of private financing of new roads. Firstly there is the model used for design build and operate the M6 Toll which has so far not performed as originally intended. This model of financing relied on private companie
defaults developing their business models based on assumptions to long range traffic growth forecasts. This meant a high level of risk was built into the model and 
defaultcosted
default accordingly
default and with regulation to toll structures or levels
default. 
default&#xa0;
default34
default.
default              
defaultThis is the model used for the M6Toll with limited benefits. 
defaultO
defaultur studies suggest that approximately 
defaultthere remains more than 30,000 vehicles per day which 
defaultpass 
defaultthrough the West Midlands (i.e. are strategic in nature)
default that could otherwise use the M6Toll if t
defaulthe apparent barriers to greater usage were addressed. 
defaultTolls appear to be now set at levels to manage MEL debt servicing rather than be aligned to road user needs and encouraging greater usage
default.
default 
default&#xa0;
default35.
default              
defaultThe M6 Toll only carries approximately half the 70,000 ve
defaulthicles per day the road was originally envisaged to carry.
default&#xa0;
default In comparison, the M6 carries 125,000 vehicles per day. This adds further weight to our view that the M6Toll needs to be fully utilised and that barriers to greater usage of the M6 Toll addressed 
defaultto maximise the economic and environmental opportunities for the West Midlands.
default&#xa0;
default3
default6
default.
default              
defaultThe second model is to use the concession model once the strategic infrastructure has been built and opened. This allows far greater certainty of risk for actual road usag
defaulte which is likely to drive a more competitive concession process to the benefit of the tax payer. This model would require 
defaultthe public sector to pump prime the infrastructure with the private sector leasing or even buying the infrastructure thereafter. 
defaultOnce
default the public sector underwriting period was complete and revenues known, growth and operating costs could be modelled and valued with certainty. The capital raised from the concession could then be recycled to fund other appropriate transport schemes. 
default&#xa0;
default3
default7
default.
default              
defaultThis model was successfully applied to the 30-year concession on 
defaultHS1 Ltd which is jointly owned and operated by Borealis Infrastructure and Ontario 
defaultTeachers
default Pension Plan until 2040 from which thereafter it is returned to Government for a concession.
default Cruci
defaultally this allows for appropriate regulation of user costs.
default&#xa0;
default3
default8
default.
default              
defaultIn summary, should the Government
default wish to better encourage private sector financing
default for new roads
default, there appears to be a better balance of risk and costs if this is pursued with the second mod
defaultel identified with the public sector building infrastructure and the private thereafter operating the infrastructure through a concession model.
default&#xa0;
